<MANSPLAIN>

Nice, BUT only IF I interpreted the (overlooked) video correctly, it actually deprives an Arduino of the knowledge of what the ...

    Address Bus
    Data Bus
    Control Bus

... are.

With the Kosmos construction kit box that I gave to my 8-year-old niece, I covered up the stupid pinhole that's default there and instead wrote:

* You can build a Flip-Flop from several transistors

* You can build a Shift Register from several Flip-Flops

* You can build an ALU from several Shift Registers

* The ALU is the most important part of a CPU

The CPU is connected to the RAMDAC (Simplest possible Graphics Card) / Peripherals / RAM/ROM with Address, Data, and Control bus. Whether access is made to the RAM chip or the ROM chip is determined by the MSB address line.

</MANSPLAIN>

Perhaps almost better would be this project here: https://eater.net/6502

Subjective opinion: the old Kosmos kits were better because the resistors still had legs like in real life.
